âYou must be well up in mathematics,â I said.  âWhere did you go to
school?â

âNever saw the inside of one, worse luck,â was the answer.  âI had to dig
it out for myself.â

âAnd why do you think I have made this thing?â he demanded, abruptly.
âDreaming to leave footprints on the sands of time?â  He laughed one of
his horrible mocking laughs.  âNot at all.  To get it patented, to make
money from it, to revel in piggishness with all night in while other men
do the work.  Thatâs my purpose.  Also, I have enjoyed working it out.â

âThe creative joy,â I murmured.

âI guess thatâs what it ought to be called.  Which is another way of
expressing the joy of life in that it is alive, the triumph of movement
