âDrop it!â Wolf Larsen cried, and the hunter dropped it as though it were
hot and had burned him.

Once aboard, the two prisoners hoisted in the boat and under Wolf
Larsenâs direction carried the wounded boat-steerer down into the
forecastle.

âIf our five boats do as well as you and I have done, weâll have a pretty
full crew,â Wolf Larsen said to me.

âThe man you shotâhe isâI hope?â Maud Brewster quavered.

âIn the shoulder,â he answered.  âNothing serious, Mr. Van Weyden will
pull him around as good as ever in three or four weeks.â

âBut he wonât pull those chaps around, from the look of it,â he added,
pointing at the _Macedoniaâs_ third boat, for which I had been steering
and which was now nearly abreast of us.  âThatâs Hornerâs and Smokeâs
work.  I told them we wanted live men, not carcasses.  But the joy of
shooting to hit is a most compelling thing, when once youâve learned how
to shoot.  Ever experienced it, Mr. Van Weyden?â

I shook my head and regarded their work.  It had indeed been bloody, for
they had drawn off and joined our other three boats in the attack on the
remaining two of the enemy.  The deserted boat was in the trough of the
