âDonât look, Miss Brewster, please donât look,â I had begged of her, and
I was glad that she had minded me and been spared the sight.

âHead right into the bunch, Mr. Van Weyden,â was Wolf Larsenâs command.

As we drew nearer, the firing ceased, and we saw that the fight was over.
The remaining two boats had been captured by our five, and the seven were
grouped together, waiting to be picked up.

âLook at that!â I cried involuntarily, pointing to the north-east.

The blot of smoke which indicated the _Macedoniaâs_ position had
reappeared.

âYes, Iâve been watching it,â was Wolf Larsenâs calm reply.  He measured
the distance away to the fog-bank, and for an instant paused to feel the
weight of the wind on his cheek.  âWeâll make it, I think; but you can
depend upon it that blessed brother of mine has twigged our little game
and is just a-humping for us.  Ah, look at that!â

The blot of smoke had suddenly grown larger, and it was very black.

âIâll beat you out, though, brother mine,â he chuckled.  âIâll beat you
out, and I hope you no worse than that you rack your old engines into
